### **HTML Basic Elements**

HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the foundation of every webpage. It uses tags to structure and display content on the web. Hereâ€™s an overview of the essential elements:

---

#### **1. Basic Structure of an HTML Document**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>My First Webpage</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to HTML</h1>
    <p>This is a basic HTML structure.</p>
</body>
</html>
```
- **`<!DOCTYPE html>`**: Declares the document type as HTML5.
- **`<html>`**: Root element of the document.
- **`<head>`**: Contains metadata like title, character set, and links to stylesheets.
- **`<body>`**: Contains the content displayed on the page.

---

#### **2. Common HTML Elements**
1. **Headings**
   - Used to define headings, from `<h1>` (largest) to `<h6>` (smallest).
   ```html
   <h1>Main Heading</h1>
   <h2>Subheading</h2>
   ```

2. **Paragraphs**
   - Use `<p>` for blocks of text.
   ```html
   <p>This is a paragraph.</p>
   ```

3. **Links**
   - Create hyperlinks with `<a>`.
   ```html
   <a href="https://example.com">Visit Example</a>
   ```

4. **Images**
   - Display images with `<img>`.
   ```html
   <img src="image.jpg" alt="Description of Image">
   ```

5. **Lists**
   - **Ordered List (`<ol>`):**
     ```html
     <ol>
         <li>First Item</li>
         <li>Second Item</li>
     </ol>
     ```
   - **Unordered List (`<ul>`):**
     ```html
     <ul>
         <li>Bullet Item</li>
         <li>Another Item</li>
     </ul>
     ```

6. **Tables**
   - Organize data in rows and columns.
   ```html
   <table>
       <tr>
           <th>Name</th>
           <th>Age</th>
       </tr>
       <tr>
           <td>John</td>
           <td>30</td>
       </tr>
   </table>
   ```

7. **Forms**
   - Collect user input.
   ```html
   <form action="/submit" method="post">
       <label for="name">Name:</label>
       <input type="text" id="name" name="name">
       <button type="submit">Submit</button>
   </form>
   ```

8. **Div and Span**
   - **`<div>`:** Block-level container for grouping content.
   - **`<span>`:** Inline container for styling text.
   ```html
   <div style="background-color: lightblue;">
       This is a block element.
   </div>
   <span style="color: red;">This is inline.</span>
   ```

---

#### **3. Attributes**
Attributes add extra information to HTML elements.
- **Common Attributes:**
  - `id`: Unique identifier.
  - `class`: For styling with CSS.
  - `style`: Inline styling.
  - `alt`: Alternative text for images.
  ```html
  <p id="intro" class="text-primary" style="font-size: 20px;">Styled Paragraph</p>
  ```

---

#### **4. Semantic Elements**
Semantic elements provide meaning to the content.
- Examples: `<header>`, `<footer>`, `<article>`, `<section>`, `<nav>`.

---

#### **Practical Exercise:**
1. Create an HTML file with:
   - A heading (`<h1>`).
   - Two paragraphs (`<p>`).
   - An image (`<img>`).
   - A link (`<a>`).
   - An ordered list (`<ol>`).

2. Use basic attributes like `id`, `class`, and `style` to format elements.

